    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"videoId":null,"videoLocaleIds":null,"bilibiliIds":null,"title":"Task 14","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p>In conversations, people often use phrases like <code>you know what</code> not to ask a real question but to share something important. It's like saying, <code>Listen, I have something to tell you.</code></p>\n<p>For example, if someone says, <code>You know what? I love ice cream,</code> they don't expect you to guess; they are just excited to tell you about their love for ice cream.</p>\n</section>","challengeType":19,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-have-a-conversation-about-preferences-and-motivations","fields":{"slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-have-a-conversation-about-preferences-and-motivations/task-14","blockName":"learn-how-to-have-a-conversation-about-preferences-and-motivations","tests":[]},"question":{"text":"<p>Why does Brian say, <code>But you know what demotivates me sometimes?</code></p>","answers":[{"answer":"<p>To ask Maria a question about demotivation</p>","feedback":"<p>Remember, <code>you know what</code> is used more for sharing, not for asking.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>To tell Maria something about himself</p>","feedback":null},{"answer":"<p>To test Maria's knowledge on demotivation</p>","feedback":"<p>Brian is sharing his feelings, not testing Maria.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>To change the subject of the conversation</p>","feedback":"<p>He's adding to the conversation, not changing the topic.</p>"}],"solution":2},"scene":{"setup":{"background":"cafe.png","characters":[{"character":"Brian","position":{"x":50,"y":15,"z":1.2},"opacity":0}],"audio":{"filename":"4.1-1.mp3","startTime":1,"startTimestamp":18.68,"finishTimestamp":26.26},"alwaysShowDialogue":null},"commands":[{"background":null,"character":"Brian","position":null,"opacity":1,"startTime":0,"finishTime":null,"dialogue":null},{"background":null,"charac